Italy, the hardest hit region in Europe, has declared 11 towns in the north of the country sealed off in the face of an outbreak of COVID-19 pneumonia, and those who violate the rules face jail or fines.

As of midnight local time on February 24, the cumulative number of confirmed cases of new pneumonia in Italy has reached 157, of which three deaths, two discharged from the hospital. Italy has also become the most affected country in Europe.

Although the first confirmed Italian case occurred in Rome, the outbreak is concentrated in northern Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. . As the source of infection is unknown, the authorities are tracking down "patient zero. ".

###11 towns closed

Eleven towns in the northern regions of Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. And Veneto were cordoned off on Sunday as a third death was reported in Italy, the Daily Telegraph and The Guardian reported on February 24.

The city closure will affect 50,000 residents in 10 municipalities in Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. And a town in the Veneto region, according to an executive order issued Saturday night by Italian Prime Minister Contes.

People are not allowed to enter or leave the 11 towns for the next two weeks without special permission. In the 11 municipalities, schools, businesses, restaurants and shops other than pharmacies were closed, all cultural, sporting and religious activities were cancelled, trains passing through the area were not allowed to stop, and residents were asked to stay at home and reduce their social activities.

Violators face penalties ranging from a fine of 206 euros to up to three months in prison. Police have begun patrolling the streets, and Contes has said troops will be deployed if needed to ensure the requirements are met.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Although Milan and Venice are not on the closed list, Milan has announced the temporary closure of the university and Milan cathedral, Milan Fashion Week activities and a series of sports events will also be affected.

Venice announced the abolition of carnival, closed museums, including ships and all means of transport for disinfection.

In Milan and other parts of Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. , people wearing masks have been lining up outside supermarkets to buy food and supplies.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Image: Twitter

Four bottles of hand sanitizer have been sold for as much as 200 euros on local Internet platforms, according to the Associated Press.

Speaking to the media, Contes said the public's concerns were understandable, but there was "no need to panic" . He called for confidence in Italy's political and scientific institutions, saying they were "doing everything possible" to contain the outbreak.

The Chinese Embassy in Italy has issued a reminder that, according to the health regulations issued by the Italian Ministry of Health on the 21st, all people who have visited the relevant areas in China within 14 days must go to the local health bureau (ASL) for the record, quarantined observation and supervision at the residence as directed by the staff of the Department of Health.

###Patient zero

The first confirmed case in Italy was a Chinese couple from Wuhan. They arrived in Italy on 23 January and were treated in Rome. The group that arrived in Italy with the two men ended their quarantine after 14 days of observation.

In addition to the couple, the third case in Rome was an Italian who had travelled to China. Although the first three cases occurred in Rome, the outbreak did not occur in Rome, but in Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. .

According to the Italian Ministry of Civil Protection Statistics, as of 23, at least 110 confirmed cases in the Lombardy region, 21 in the adjacent Veneto region.

In the face of a sudden outbreak, civil protection minister Angelo Borrelli noted that there was still no "patient zero" who could carry and spread the virus.

The first confirmed case in Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. Was a 38-year-old researcher at the Unilever branch in the town of Casalpustelungo.

The man had not been to China recently but had dinner with a friend who had returned to Italy from Shanghai in late January. And my friend tested negative for the virus.

After the man was diagnosed, his pregnant wife and a runner were also diagnosed with the infection. The runner's father owns a bar in the town of Cordoño, and three elderly patrons who frequent the bar have been diagnosed. The town of cordoño is only 10 minutes'drive from the town of Casalpustellongo.

On Saturday, a 77-year-old woman was confirmed dead. The patient had been to the emergency room of a hospital in the town of Cordoño, where the first confirmed man had stopped shortly before his arrival.

More than 120 of the man's colleagues and a doctor who had visited his home were under quarantine.

In addition to the man, the authorities at one point focused their investigation on local Chinese residents.

The man had frequented a cafe before his diagnosis, and more than Chinese residents were frequent customers. But the Chinese residents tested negative for the virus.

Attilio Fontana, the president of Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. , said: "Unfortunately, the people who thought they were patient zero are not patient zero. We need to look elsewhere. ". Fontana said there were two scenarios in which authorities would track down patient zero.

With the outbreak in Italy, neighboring Austria is ready to take precautions.

On Sunday, a train from Italy to Germany was stopped before it entered Austria because two passengers had fever. Austria then suspended all trains to and from Italy. It was not until four hours later, when two passengers tested negative, that the trains were resumed in Austria.

Austria has considered restarting border controls with Italy after the setback. Although both countries are Schengen zone countries, in exceptional circumstances member states can reactivate border controls. The Austrian government is due to discuss border controls on Monday.

Italy's other neighbour, Switzerland, remains on the fence. Swiss health officials said that while the situation in Italy was worrying, it was "too early to tell" whether the outbreak would spread to Switzerland.

France, not far from the Italian blockade, said new cases were likely and that it was procuring medical equipment to prepare for the possibility of a pandemic.

The German Ministry of Health has announced that it will hold a conference call with the European Union's public health authorities on Monday to discuss the outbreak in northern Italy and the response.
